<!-- M2-A1/B6: declarative least-privilege `bullpen` app user (plan 0.4's users.d approach,
     executed at the 2026-07-03 window). COMMITTED TEMPLATE - the real users.d/bullpen.xml
     is RENDERED (gitignored) by infra/clickhouse/render-users.sh, which substitutes the
     sha256 hex of BULLPEN_CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD. No plaintext and no crackable hash in git.

     GRANTS LIVE IN THIS FILE, not in SQL (box finding, 2026-07-03 window): XML-defined
     users sit in a read-only access storage - `GRANT ... TO bullpen` via SQL fails with
     ACCESS_STORAGE_READONLY - and an XML user with NO <grants> block silently gets FULL
     access, which is the exact inversion of what a least-privilege user is for. So the
     <grants> block below is load-bearing: removing it does not lock the user down, it
     opens the box up.

     Grant shape (option A + the ALTER addition, owner-approved 2026-07-03). Each grant maps
     to a real thing the app does, all under default.* (the app connects to the default DB):
       SELECT, INSERT      - the runtime surface: reads (serving, drift, truth-join) and
                             appends (prediction_log, pitches_live, drift_metrics).
       CREATE TABLE        - the app boot-time migration runner (ClickHouseMigrationRunner,
                             @PostConstruct, every boot) issues CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS
                             _schema_migrations UNCONDITIONALLY before anything else, and CH
                             checks the CREATE privilege BEFORE evaluating IF NOT EXISTS - so
                             even on an already-migrated DB a CREATE-less user cannot boot.
                             (The versioned CREATE TABLE migrations are SKIPPED once applied;
                             the tracking table is the real driver.)
       ALTER ADD COLUMN,   - the SAME migration runner REPLAYS any unapplied migration as this
       ALTER MODIFY COLUMN   user, and ~12 of the migrations are ALTER TABLE ADD/MODIFY COLUMN.
                             Without these, the next ALTER-bearing migration deploy, or a
                             clean/restored-DB boot as bullpen (rule-8 restore, DR - the runner
                             replays from V002 and dies at the first ALTER), fails app startup.
                             Found latent by the M2-B adversarial verification.
     Deliberately ABSENT (the destructive ops this user exists to make impossible, defense in
     depth behind the block-destructive-ch session hook a plain clickhouse-client bypasses):
     DROP TABLE, TRUNCATE, ALTER DROP COLUMN, and mutations (ALTER UPDATE / ALTER DELETE),
     RENAME. New DDL outside this set is a re-decision, not a quiet grant widening.

     Verification (matches the executed B6 ceremony), as user bullpen:
       SELECT 1                   -> ok
       INSERT INTO ...            -> ok
       ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN -> ok
       DROP TABLE prediction_log  -> DENIED

     access_management=0: the bullpen user cannot GRANT/CREATE USER/etc. The `default`
     user keeps access_management=1 (compose env) and remains the admin identity.

     Applying changes: users.d edits require a ClickHouse container FORCE-RECREATE (the
     single-file bind mount goes stale on an inode swap, and CH reads users.d only at
     startup). render-users.sh prints the exact compose recreate command on every render.

     Rollback: revert BULLPEN_CLICKHOUSE_USER to `default` in /etc/default/bullpen (+ the
     backup env) and restart api+worker - the default user stays fully functional until a
     later cleanup pass removes it from the app path. -->
<clickhouse>
    <users>
        <bullpen>
            <password_sha256_hex>__BULLPEN_CLICKHOUSE_PASSWORD_SHA256__</password_sha256_hex>
            <networks>
                <ip>::/0</ip>
            </networks>
            <profile>default</profile>
            <quota>default</quota>
            <access_management>0</access_management>
            <grants>
                <query>GRANT SELECT, INSERT ON default.*</query>
                <query>GRANT CREATE TABLE ON default.*</query>
                <query>GRANT ALTER ADD COLUMN, ALTER MODIFY COLUMN ON default.*</query>
            </grants>
        </bullpen>
    </users>
</clickhouse>
